title: For Sale/Trade:  Three (3) motorcycles
postcontent:
I have 3 bikes I am looking to trade or sell.  I will trade any combination of bikes for a gun or a single bike for a gun or whatever.  Really only interested in legitimate classic / antique guns, Rem 700's, AR's (.223 or .308), .50 cal, etc.  Bikes below:

1) 1977 Suzuki GS750 street tracker build:

Just finished this thing up after almost 3 years. It has been an on again / off again project for me. Runs and rides great as it sits. Here is the jist:

1977 Suzuki GS750. Clean title. Bought as a project and completed the following: took it apart to the frame and engine, new (used) instrument bezel, new handle bars, 06-07 GSXR front master cylinder and resevoir, front stainless braided brake line, rebuilt rear master and resevoir, rear stainless braided brake line, new valve shims within spec, new front sprocket, new rear sprocket, new chain, new gaskets all around (except for head and cylinder), new air filter, new cylinder head intake boots, cleaned and completely rebuilt carbs, new clutch cable, new brake pads, rebuilt front and rear calipers, new plug caps, new clutch springs, new allen head engine hardware kit, cleaned up and fixed wiring. All electronics work. New tires. New grips. Have tons of spares and stock parts. Also have case savers that are not installed. Painted valve cover caps, head light bezel, headers and slip ons, and rear fender flat black (sand blasted, primed and painted, headers and slip ons were painted with high temp exhaust paint). Oil and filter are new. Battery is new, and kick start works also. New spark plugs.

A test ride is possible with CASH IN HAND.

$2500 as it sits (Rear fender has tail light mounting holes in it, forks need a rebuild...thats about all it needs.) If you want me to complete that stuff, we might be able to figure something out.

Comes With: Case savers, 2 more oil filters, all the stock stuff I removed (rear fender, old brake lines, blinkers, tail light, etc, etc.)

I can take as many pictures of whatever you want on this bike, and will answer all questions, just shoot me an email. 
____________________________________________
2) 2003 Yamaha TTR250:

A little over 2000 miles, new brake pads front and rear, 99% front tire, 75% rear tire, aftermarket rear fender and tail light, newer battery, carb was new a bout 800 miles ago. Ive added a skid plate and a windscreen that stay with the bike. Seat is in excellent condition with no tears.

The first picture shows how I had it set up for dual sport use for Tellico and Citico and cruising around town so that you can see what it looks like kitted out. However the Wolfman bags, bark busters / hand guards, and tank bag don't come with the bike.

I changed the oil with Rotella, lubed the chain, and cleaned the air filter regularly. When the bike was stored for the winter, it was run once a week and had Stabil in the fuel. It comes with a couple extra oil filters and the stock tail section.

$2000 obo, but that doesn't mean Ill give it away. The bike has some rough spots visually, like the plastic over the muffler, but I never cared since it was covered by pannier bags. Mechanically though, the bike is excellent, and I have ridden it to and from Citico and Tellico many times with 0 issues. I rode it all the way to Cleveland TN and back on 411 last summer with no problems.  Clean Title.
___________________________________

3) 1994 Suzuki DR125:

1100-1200 miles (not sure, will check), good tires, rebuilt carb, all original, all lights and accessories work.  This was my wifes bike when we would ride around Citico and Tellico.  Street legal dual sport, clean title. $1200 obo.

Constructed from Mil-Spec hard-anodized aluminum, they feed smoothly and reliably due to optimal geometry, non-binding coil springs, and ingenious nesting polymer followers. The long-lasting springs are cadmium coated for low friction and excellent corrosion resistance. Magazines require no lubricants and can be easily disassembled without tools for cleaning.

SureFire High-Capacity magazines provide distinct tactical advantages: increased initial firepower in ambush situations; fewer reloads overall, which means less downtime and target distraction in a firefight; fast and easy magazine insertion, even with a closed bolt; less bulk compared to drum mags, enabling a normal weapon grip. The 60-round magazine—slightly thinner than two 30-round magazines clipped together and about the same overall length—fits in most dual magazine pouches, eliminating special carry pouches required for drum magazines.

title: For Sale:  Colt Peacekeeper .357 Magnum
postcontent:
Up for sale is a Colt Peacekeeper .357 Magnum with the 6inch barrel this gun is used but is in great shape. These pistols were manufactured only during 1985-87, and are very similar to the Colt Trooper. The finish is a matte black, Parkerized in appearance. Legend has it that the Colt factory polishers were on strike, so the initial batch was shipped with the matte finish. When the polishers returned from the strike, Colt put them to work on their backlog of other pistols and continued to manufacture the Peacekeeper with the parkerized look. This particular gun is the six inch model. No box, no papers... just an outstanding gun. If you have any questions regarding this gun or others we have feel free to give us a call, send us a email, or stop in and check out our large selection!
